[[File:BedikGirls.jpg|right|thumb|160px|Bedick girls, Iwol village]] The '''Bedick''', or '''Bedik''', are a minority [[ethnic group]] of Africa.<ref>[http://www.sit.edu/studyabroad/program_content/contents.cfm?include=sgr_excursions.html&progCode=ssa.sgr Senegal: Arts and Culture:Kedougou: Ethnic Minorities Discovery] at [[School for International Training]]</ref> They live in villages in the most isolated area of eastern [[Senegal]], in the [[Arrondissement of Bandafassi]].<ref>[http://www.idrc.ca/en/ev-43036-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html BANDAFASSI DSS, SENEGAL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071208032059/http://www.idrc.ca/en/ev-43036-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html |date=2007-12-08 }}</ref> [[Iwol]] is one of their settlements.
The Bedick speak the [[Bedik language]] [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=tnr] and their religion is a [[syncretism|blend]] between their [[animist]] roots and a more recent [[Christian]] influence. More connected with [[Guinea Conakry]] or [[Mali]] than with Senegal, Bedick people have contact with other ethnic groups like [[Bassari]] and [[Serer people|Serer]]. Their ancestors are the families Keita and Camera that came from Mali because of the War led by [[Alpha Yaye]] coming from [[Fouta Djalon]].
